### Is this a regression?

No, this code hasn't been changed in at least a year.

### Description

There are two issues in the `visitJsonSchema` function:

- The `visitJsonSchema` function incorrectly handles `'items'` property as a part of `propsKeywords` while it should be `keywords`. It's already present in `keywords`, but overruled due to `propsKeywords`.
  https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/blob/b3ed8aa4ad6736130bd9603ebf681b229c16f2b2/packages/angular_devkit/core/src/json/schema/visitor.ts#L169-L176
  https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/blob/b3ed8aa4ad6736130bd9603ebf681b229c16f2b2/packages/angular_devkit/core/src/json/schema/visitor.ts#L153-L156
- The visitor passes the grandparent schema object rather than the parent schema when visiting any of the `propsKeywords` values (`sch` vs. `schema` at line 197).
  https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/blob/b3ed8aa4ad6736130bd9603ebf681b229c16f2b2/packages/angular_devkit/core/src/json/schema/visitor.ts#L189-L201
  This breaks the visitor in flatten as it tries to replace a `$ref` with the value it references:
  https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/blob/b3ed8aa4ad6736130bd9603ebf681b229c16f2b2/packages/angular_devkit/core/src/json/schema/registry.ts#L288

These two bugs each lead to `CoreSchemaRegistry#flatten` not actually flattening properties inside items.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

Executing the following file will print `{ '$ref': '#/definitions/pattern' }`

<details><summary>Toggle file</summary>

```js
const {json} = require('@angular-devkit/core');

const registry = new json.schema.CoreSchemaRegistry();

registry
  .flatten({
    type: 'object',
    properties: {
      assets: {
        type: 'array',
        items: {
          type: 'object',
          properties: {
            include: {
              $ref: '#/definitions/pattern',
            },
            exclude: {
              $ref: '#/definitions/pattern',
            },
          },
        },
      },
    },
    definitions: {
      pattern: {
        oneOf: [
          {
            type: 'string',
          },
          {
            type: 'array',
            items: {
              type: 'string',
            },
          },
        ],
      },
    },
  })
  .subscribe(flattened => {
    console.log(flattened.properties.assets.items.properties.include);
  });
```

